\nowidctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \rtlch\fcs1 \af31507\afs22\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\loch\af31506\hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f0\lang9\langfe1033\langnp9\insrsid6447502\charrsid12406749 \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 Tables (or Relations):}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\lang9\langfe1033\langnp9\insrsid6447502\charrsid12406749 \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 
 The fundamental building block of a relational database. Each table is made up of rows and columns.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f0\lang9\langfe1033\langnp9\insrsid6447502\charrsid12406749 \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 Rows (or Tuples/Records):}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\lang9\langfe1033\langnp9\insrsid6447502\charrsid12406749 
\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0  Represent a single, complete entry of data in a table. For example, a row in a "Customers" table would contain all the information for one customer.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f0\lang9\langfe1033\langnp9\insrsid6447502\charrsid12406749 \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 Columns (or Attributes/Fields): }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\lang9\langfe1033\langnp9\insrsid6447502\charrsid12406749 
\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 Represent specific categories of data. In a "Cus\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 tomers" table, columns might include "CustomerID," "Name," and "Email."
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f0\lang9\langfe1033\langnp9\insrsid6447502\charrsid12406749 \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 Keys:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\lang9\langfe1033\langnp9\insrsid6447502\charrsid12406749 \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 
 Special columns used to link tables and enforce data integrity.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f0\lang9\langfe1033\langnp9\insrsid6447502\charrsid12406749 \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 Primary Key:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\lang9\langfe1033\langnp9\insrsid6447502\charrsid12406749 
\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0  A column (or set of columns) that uniquely identifies each row in a table. No two rows can have the\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0  same primary key value.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f0\lang9\langfe1033\langnp9\insrsid6447502\charrsid12406749 \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 Foreign Key:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\lang9\langfe1033\langnp9\insrsid6447502\charrsid12406749 
\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0  A column in one table that references the primary key of another table. This is how relationships are formed. For example, an "Orders" table might have a CustomerID foreign key that links to the CustomerID primary key
\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0  in the "Customers" table.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f0\lang9\langfe1033\langnp9\insrsid6447502\charrsid12406749 \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 Structured Query Language (SQL):}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\lang9\langfe1033\langnp9\insrsid6447502\charrsid12406749 
\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0  The standard language used to interact with relational databases. SQL allows you to create, read, update, and delete data, as well as define the database structure.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f0\lang9\langfe1033\langnp9\insrsid6447502\charrsid12406749 \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 How It Works
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\lang9\langfe1033\langnp9\insrsid6447502\charrsid12406749 \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 The core idea of\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 
 a relational database is to reduce data redundancy and maintain data integrity by "normalizing" the data. Instead of storing all information in one giant, complex table, you break it down into smaller, more manageable tables with specific purposes.

\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 For e\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 xample, imagine a database for an online store. Instead of a single table with all customer, order, and product details, you would have separate tables for:
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 Customers: Stores customer information (e.g., CustomerID, Name, Address).
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 Products: Stores produc\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 t information (e.g., ProductID, Name, Price).
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 Orders: Stores order information, linking to the Customers and Products tables using foreign keys.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 By using this relational model, if a customer's address changes, you only need to update it in one place (the\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0  Customers table), which avoids inconsistencies and errors.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f0\lang9\langfe1033\langnp9\insrsid6447502\charrsid12406749 \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 Relational vs. Non-Relational Databases
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\lang9\langfe1033\langnp9\insrsid6447502\charrsid12406749 \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 
Relational databases are often compared to NoSQL (non-relational) databases, which have a more flexible, schema-less structure. The choice between the two \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 depends on the type of data and the application's requirements.

\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 Feature\tab Relational Databases\tab NoSQL Databases
\par }\pard\plain \ltrpar\s15\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid12406749 \rtlch\fcs1 \af31507\afs22\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 
\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\loch\af31506\hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\lang9\langfe1033\langnp9\insrsid12406749 \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 Data Structure Tabular with a fixed schema. }{
