\f0\lang9\langfe1033\langnp9\insrsid6447502\charrsid12406749 \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 Document Model: Used in databases like MongoDB, the document model is the most prominent example of an aggreg\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 
ate data model. Each document is a self-contained aggregate, storing all related information. For example, a single document for a product might include its name, price, description, and an array of reviews.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 Key-Value Model: The simplest form of an aggrega\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 te model. Each key maps to a single value, which can be a complex object. The key and its value together form an aggregate.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 Wide-Column Model: While column-oriented, databases like Cassandra can be seen as using an aggregate model where a row is an aggreg\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 
ate. This row can contain multiple column families, with all the data for one entity stored together for fast retrieval.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f0\ul\lang9\langfe1033\langnp9\insrsid6447502\charrsid12406749 \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 Why Use Aggregate Models?}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\lang9\langfe1033\langnp9\insrsid6447502\charrsid12406749 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 Aggregate data models are popular in NoSQL because they are well-suited for several modern application needs\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 :
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 
Read-heavy applications: By storing all related data in a single document, a single query can retrieve all the necessary information, eliminating the need for complex, resource-intensive JOIN operations that are common in relational databases. This dras
\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 tically improves read performance.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 Scalability: The aggregate-centric design aligns with the distributed nature of NoSQL databases. Since data is a self-contained unit, it can be easily partitioned and distributed across different servers, enabling horizo
\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 ntal scaling.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 Flexibility: The schema-less nature of aggregate models allows for quick and easy modifications to the data structure without affecting the entire database, which is a major advantage in agile development environments.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f0\ul\insrsid6447502\charrsid12406749 \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 1.7 Distribution Model\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 s
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\insrsid6447502\charrsid12406749 \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 
A distribution model is a strategy for organizing and managing how data is stored across multiple nodes (servers) in a distributed database system. Its primary goal is to improve performance, scalability, and fault tolerance by avoiding a single point of
\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0  failure and enabling parallel processing.
