\f0\insrsid6447502\charrsid12406749 \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 Node: A single computer or server in a distributed system that stores a portion of the database.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 Cluster: A collection of interconnected nodes working together as a single, logical database.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 Partit\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 
ioning (Sharding): The process of splitting a single logical database into smaller, more manageable pieces called partitions or shards. Each shard is stored on a separate node. This is the core principle behind most distribution models.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 Common Distribution Models
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 There are three main ways to partition and distribute data:
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 Shared-Nothing Architecture: This is the most common model in modern NoSQL databases. Each node is an independent unit with its own CPU, memory, and storage. Nodes don'\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 
t share any resources, and data is partitioned across them. This architecture is highly scalable and fault-tolerant because a failure on one node does not affect the others.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 Shared-Disk Architecture: In this model, all nodes have independent CPUs and memo\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 
ry but share a common storage device. This simplifies management because all data is accessible from any node. However, it can create a bottleneck at the shared storage, and if the storage fails, the entire system can go down.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 Shared-Memory Architecture: \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 
This is the least common model for distributed databases. All nodes share access to a single, common memory space. This is very fast but is not scalable and is not fault-tolerant, as a failure in the shared memory brings down the entire system.
