\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\insrsid6447502\charrsid12406749 \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 The way data is partitioned significantly impacts performance. Two common strategies are:
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 Hashing: A hash function is applied to a primary key to determine which node a piece of data belongs to. This provides a uniform distribution of data, \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 
which is good for avoiding hot spots (nodes that receive more requests than others). However, it can make range queries less efficient as related data may be spread across different nodes.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 Range-Based Partitioning: Data is partitioned based on a range of \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 
key values. For example, all users with IDs from 1 to 1000 might be on Node 1, and users from 1001 to 2000 might be on Node 2. This is excellent for range queries but can lead to uneven data distribution if certain ranges have more data than others.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f0\ul\insrsid6447502\charrsid12406749 \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 1.8 Ap\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 proaches to data distribution
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\insrsid6447502\charrsid12406749 \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 
Data distribution is the practice of storing and managing a database across multiple physical or logical nodes. The goal is to enhance scalability, performance, and availability by avoiding a single point of failure and enabli
\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 ng parallel processing. The two primary approaches to data distribution are replication and sharding, which can be used individually or in combination.
\par 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f0\insrsid6447502\charrsid12406749 \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 Replication
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\insrsid6447502\charrsid12406749 \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 Replication involves creating and maintaining multiple copies of the same data on differen\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 
t nodes. The main purpose is to increase read throughput, data availability, and fault tolerance. If one node fails, the system can continue to operate using a replica.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 Master-Slave Replication: In this model, one node is designated as the master, which\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 
 handles all write operations. The other nodes, called slaves, contain copies of the data and are used for read operations. The master node sends updates to the slaves to keep them synchronized.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 Peer-to-Peer Replication: Also known as multi-master replica\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 
tion, this model allows any node to accept both read and write operations. The updates are then synchronized with all other nodes in the cluster. This provides higher write scalability and resilience but introduces complexity in maintaining data consisten
\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 c\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 y.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f0\insrsid6447502\charrsid12406749 \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 Sharding (or Partitioning)
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\insrsid6447502\charrsid12406749 \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 
Sharding is the process of splitting a single database into smaller, independent pieces called shards, and distributing these shards across different nodes. Each shard contains a unique subset of the data. This approach is primarily used for horizontal sc
\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 a\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 ling to handle large datasets that don't fit on a single server.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f0\insrsid6447502\charrsid12406749 \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 Hash-Based Sharding:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\insrsid6447502\charrsid12406749 \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 
 A hash function is applied to a primary key (e.g., a user ID) to determine which shard a data record belongs to. This approach tends to distribute data evenly across al\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 
l nodes, preventing hot spots. However, it can make range queries inefficient because related data might be scattered across different shards.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f0\insrsid6447502\charrsid12406749 \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 Range-Based Sharding:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\insrsid6447502\charrsid12406749 \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 
 Data is partitioned based on a range of key values. For example, customer data with last n\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 
ames from 'A' to 'M' could be stored on one shard, while 'N' to 'Z' could be on another. This makes range queries very efficient but can lead to uneven data distribution if some ranges contain more data than others, creating hot spots.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f0\insrsid6447502\charrsid12406749 \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 Directory-Based Sha\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 rding:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\insrsid6447502\charrsid12406749 \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 
 This model uses a lookup service or directory to map keys to their corresponding shards. This provides flexibility and makes it easy to add or remove nodes, as the mapping can be updated in the directory without affecting the entire cluster.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f0\insrsid6447502\charrsid12406749 \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 Combin\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 ing Replication and Sharding
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\insrsid6447502\charrsid12406749 \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 
In many real-world systems, these two approaches are combined for maximum benefit. For instance, a sharded database can use replication within each shard. This means each shard is a small cluster with a master-slave or multi-ma
\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 ster replication setup. This provides both horizontal scalability (sharding) and high availability (replication) for each data partition.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f0\ul\insrsid6447502\charrsid12406749 
